# Distributions

## What is a distribution?
A software distribution or *distro* is a version of that software that has been altered or comes with a collection of predecided and curated components or other software out of the box. Many popular programs from web browser, to text editors, to oeprating systems have various distros that can be chosen from. The process of creating a distribution of software can be called *forking*, becuase that software is now forking or branching off into something else. And maybe that fork will be forked itself. This process of creating and forking new distros of software can create a tree like structure with branches spanning out from other branches based on the distros' familial relationships. 

## Linux Distributions
And Linux is definitly no exception. There are countless distros, sometimes referred to as *flavors*, currently in active development and maittenance. The vast amount of distros can be daunting and even parallyzing to a new suer, but it seems that these sentiments arise from misconceptions regarding the differences is distros.

