## The Differences
Most distributions are going to have aesthetic and functional differences between the graphical use rinterfaces that come pre-installed on the system. However, in many cases this is simply an aesthetic difference that can be changed as distros often support multiple graphica lenvironemtns. You will learn mopre about graphical user enviornments or *GUIs* in the later chapter: [Elements of a Linux Graphical User Interface](). This is aklso true for most software that is installed by default on a distro; it can simply be uninstalled or replaced. Beyond these asesthic and more ephermeral differences, there are three more non trivial differences between distros:

* Update Delivery
* Package Availability
* Initilization System

### Update Delivery 
There are three types of software update delivery paradigms on Linux. There is *rolling release*, *fixed release*, and *semi-rolling release*. A fixed release distro such as Red Hat or Debian have versions that are updated anually along with software repositories. Usually avalable software on these distros can be relativly dated. A rolling realse distro however does not have versions. Instead the lates software is avaialble as it become available. In this case you have access to the latest versions of software. And a semi-rolling release is a combination of the two, where a mojor update is rolled out anually, but users have access to the latest software in *most* cases. All this being said, distros that are fixed usually are more *stable* and more free of bugs, issues, and conflicts, and suited for use on servers. 

### Package Avaiability
Distros differ in that some have more programs or *packages* available for install than other. This is becuase those who maintain the distro have made that software aviaiuble within that distro's *repositories*. You will learn more about packages and software repositoreies in the later chapter [Packaging Systems & Package Management]().

### Initilization Systems
Some distros have different initilization or *init* systems. The most prominent init system is SystemD. Other init systems exist, but are found on systems far less today. You wil learn about init systems i nthe later chapter: []().


